## Where the two voices diverge

### THWB voice: reflective, literary, unhurried

THWB is the brand that thinks out loud. The voice is essayistic,
warm, confident, sometimes funny, often quiet. It sounds like a
Sunday morning conversation at the kitchen table with a couple
you trust.

**THWB sounds like:**
- Substack at its best
- Kinfolk magazine's writing
- A Ta-Nehisi Coates personal essay
- A great Tim Ferriss intro
- Your wisest friend who also happens to be funny

**THWB avoids:**
- Hustle language
- Marketing speak
- Urgency
- "Game-changing" or any hype word
- Lists of 10 Things You Must Know
- Clickbait

**THWB example:**

> On Sunday nights, we used to fight. Not loudly. Just that tired,
> quiet fighting that happens when two people have been pulling
> the wagon in different directions all week and nobody has the
> energy to name it.
>
> The fix wasn't more love. We had plenty of that. The fix was a
> meeting. Thirty minutes. Every Sunday. Same time, same couch.
> And a format so simple it felt almost embarrassing the first
> time we tried it.

### Trellis voice: direct, confident, capable

Trellis is the product. The voice is clear, specific, and
builder-like. It sounds like a well-designed tool that respects
your time. Premium but not cold. Friendly but not cute.

**Trellis sounds like:**
- Linear's product pages
- Oura's marketing site
- A Stripe docs page when it's doing its job
- A confident founder explaining what their product actually does

**Trellis avoids:**
- Marketing fluff
- "Revolutionize" / "transform" / any empty verb
- Long philosophical paragraphs (save those for THWB)
- Feature lists without context
- Startup speak

**Trellis example:**

> Trellis pulls both your calendars. Day by day. Cy asks two
> to four questions per day. You commit to five decisions. You
> walk into Monday clear.
>
> $29/month. All 11 pillars. Both parents. Every kid. One app.

